Christmas decorations and illuminations take on a larger-than-life presence in London. It spans stories revolving around the Northern Lights, Greek gods, Norwegian World War troops, the drawing rooms of Downton Abbey to schoolboy yarn of the Hardy Boys.

From the old-world shopping passageways Burlington Arcade and Liberty's, to watt-wielding LED Christmas trees on Trafalgar Square, to ultra-chic, fluorescent boutiques of Mayfair to the ethereal angels of Regent Street, interwoven wreaths of Seven Dials and a puffed, mistletoe-lined disco ball in Covent Garden

A monumental structure that houses a replica of the curio-studded hall in Paris' Versailles Palace and the Statue of Liberty, the towering American landmark on Ellis Island. 
The Edificio la Prensa stands triumphant weathering turn of presidencies, invasion of the Falklands, closing of Congress and legislative ban on trade unions and the deposing of President Peron.

Known as the Buenos Aires House of Culture, this magnificent structure is a former press headquarters, where the daily conservative newspaper La Prensa was printed. The Falklands Invasion of 1982 by the British was covered by this broadsheet.

Recreating the once revered heyday of the French Court, it features a man with book and torch in tow, similar to the vainglorious Statue of Liberty. This was in itself a gift from the French to the United States. 
Ringing a giant bell from the courtyard once signalled to the public, an event of national signficance.
Shopping galleries look like statuesque architectural marvels in Argentina

A quaint forested nature reserve within La Plata, the smaller sister city of Buenos Aires. With colourful pedal boats, an amphitheatre and observatory and assortment of flowers, the Paseo del Bosque is dubbed the "forest of La Plata". Expansive tree groves of eucalyptus, poplars and oaks and wild geese and swans work together to create an atmosphere of imagined seclusion.

Incredible biodiversity and paleontology exhibits at the Natural History Museum in La Plata, a swift bus ride outside of Buenos Aires. Particularly fascinating is the Egypt Hall, which charts early construction of settlements in Aswan, Egypt.
Smoky, charred mixed parilla, medialunas (Argentine croissants), spinach omelette and pumpkin tart

Like cities including New York City, London, Melbourne, Berlin, Tokyo, Tel Aviv, Beirut, Lisbon, Rishikesh (North India), Cape Town, Istanbul, Havana, Cairo, Penang and so much more, Buenos Aires is a haven for street art. The voice of the street is pulsating and ponderous, making allusions to its fragmented society.

In La Boca, the cobbled, dog poo-soiled streets, kneel of hammering cobblers, fastidious streetside florists and wafts of parilla barbecue lend to an invigorating atmosphere.
Interior of a Japanese restaurant complete with Tibetan mandalas, calligraphy scrolls, exotic pottery and an ornate shrine.
Used bookstores in Buenos Aires are as commonplace as a convenience store. Love their vintage pushcart set-up!
Birds of Buenos Aires
From flea markets, the theatre district, zinc shacks, mouldy tenements, livewire junctions to loud, exuberant highways, Buenos Aires' street art has it all.
Meals of Christmas in many flavours -- Lebanese kebabs and tabouleh, British beef Wellington and Argentine mushroom glazed chicken
Lomito steak sandwich and grilled chorizo: Argentine national treasure

Known as the Pope's Church, the Cathedral Metropolitano de Buenos Aires features a sculpture of the Virgin Mary. Also in its interior are a mausoleum, massive organ, an astounding classical painting of Jesus before being nailed to the cross and Baroque, French Neoclassical and Italian Renaissance stylistic elements.
Edifico Otto Wulff, a splendid Art Deco structure filled with the state emblems of Austria and Hungary and intriguing sculptures of a thinker's pose, draftsman, carpenter and wrestler among others.

Made up jointly of an artist colony and working class neighbourhood, La Boca is a tourist draw with its varnished, multicoloured houses. Known as conventillos, these makeshift shacks have been in existence for some 70 years.

Robert Sullivan once likened good architecture to an effective therapy session, a solid marriage or a powerful poem -- "gently and almost invisibly allowing you to be you, flawed or beautiful as you are." Amidst the chronic state dysfunctions, of a tattered social system and problematised, disheartened outlook, Buenos Aires' buildings stand upright and high-spirited.

In their own expression, imagination and salvation, it's like a promise that life will start all over despite the blocks and cracks.

Buenos Aires' most formidable city square -- Plaza del Congreso. A city of disconcertingly stark disparity, a fence was built to prevent vandals and delinquents from defacing the powerful structure, Congreso, a symbol of liberty and lost ideals.

Remembering this Xmas to be grateful for all the life experience and ability to experience new cultures and world views. 
Abuzz with joire de vivre, Argentina is a joyous musical. Witness memorable exchanges through winsome tango moves, eclectic styles from its architecture to its cinema, deep roots to its history and a diverse spin of sentiments. In the land of the gaucho, people stand for their opinions and there is no conciliation, only the magnetic pull of extremes.

Many thanks @alejandromartinm for having me as your guest and sharing this amazing, delicious Xmas meal with me!

Under my umbrella

Westminster Abbey, London vs St Pedro Gonzales Telmo, Buenos Aires.

The Abbey with its decorated clientle of royalty, novelists, scientists and explorers, yells prestige from its vaulting ceilings, brushes of electrifying gold to cavernous worship spaces. Indeed, the organ centrepiece has been on television globally thanks to fanfare over royal weddings and the Coronation.

Gonzales Telmo is obviously far more understated but steeped in its own character. The Buenos Aires institution was founded on enlightening the poor and has seen persecution and controversy. It has weathered decay, cultural decline, epidemics and the loosening of morals. 
Today, Gonzales stands singularly in a neighbourhood now identified for decibel-crunching cumbia, passionate embraces of tango, farmer's and souvenir markets and the joys of alleyway football.

Sky views from an exquisitely designed towering skyscraper. Palacio Barolo is filled with references to fictional dragons and serpents, Italian literature, Hindu worship sites, Greco mythology and winding stairs simulating purgatory.
Life goals: Inking a trade deal between LATAM and ASEAN
